**Abstract:**
Major essay dated September 9, 1996 titled "The Epistemic Subject after Post-Modernism." Argues post-modernism brings the Greek epistemic tradition to closure. Develops critique of "visibility assumption" - the model of knowledge as seeing. Contrasts the "epistemic model of visibility" with the "epistemic model of affectibility" based on the exposed, vulnerable agent-patient. Proposes dramatic narratives as alternative to speculative knowledge.

**AI Recommendation:** Central theoretical text; synthesizes critique of Greek epistemology. Links to 96-SEP-1, 96-OCT series.

